  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions. It typically falls under criminal legislation and is considered a serious financial crime. Specific laws and penalties vary by country, but money laundering generally involves:\n\n1. Concealing the origin of illegally obtained money\n2. Transforming \"dirty\" money into seemingly \"clean\" money\n3. Trying to make illegally obtained funds appear legitimate\n\nIn many countries, money laundering is prosecuted under:\n- Criminal codes\n- Anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Financial crime statutes\n- Proceeds of crime legislation\n\nPenalties can include:\n- Substantial fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n- Professional sanctions\n\nInternational organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) work to establish global standards for combating money laundering.",
